media.plainText: italian term describing the way pasta is cooked so its texture is slightly resistant to the bite.
to spoon pan juices, melted fat, or another liquid over the surface of food during cooking to keep the food moist and add flavor.
to mix ingredients together with a circular up and down motion using a spoon, whisk, or rotary or electric beater.
to scald or parboil in water or steam
to stir ingredients until they are thoroughly combined.
to cook in liquid at 212 degrees fahreheit
To cut or slice cooked meat, poultry, fish, or game into serving-size pieces
a large deep dish in which food can be served
to make food cold by placing it in a refrigerator or in a bowl over crushed ice
to mix or blend two or more ingredients together
to thoroughly cover food with a liquid or dry mixture
to cut into small squares of equal size
To cause semisolid pieces of coagulated protein to develop in a dairy product
combine solid fat with flour using a pastry blender, two forks, or fingers
Refers to a small amount of seasoning that is added to food. It is generally between 1/16 and 1/8 teaspoon. The term is often used for liquid ingredients, such as bottled hot pepper sauce
mixture that forms when oil and liquid mix together
To add visual appeal to a finished dish
An elastic protein present in flour, especially wheat flour, that provides most of the structure of baked products.
to work dough by pressing it with the heels of the hands, folding it, turning it, and repeating each motion until the dough is smooth
To gently swirl one food into another. Marbling is usually done with light and dark batters for cakes or cookies.
A seasoned liquid in which meat, poultry, fish, shellfish, or vegetables are soaked to flavor and sometimes tenderize them. Most marinades contain an acid, such as wine or vinegar
To heat a solid food, such as chocolate, margarine, or butter, over very low heat until it becomes liquid or semi-liquid
to cut or chop into very fine pieces
to combine two or more ingredients into a mass
To slowly heat a beverage, such as cider, with spices and sugar
to remove the steam and outer covering of a veggie or fruit with a paring knife or peeler
To force a semisoft food, such as whipped cream or frosting, through a pastry bag to decorate food
To remove the seed from fruit
To cook a food by partially or completely submerging it in a simmering liquid
To heat an oven or a utensil to a specific temperature before using it.
To process or mash a food until it is as smooth as possible. This can be done using a blender, food processor, sieve, or food mill; also refers to the resulting mixture.
a chart showing the amount of in take needed of different food groups
to cook food in a small amount of hot fat
to make small, shallow cuts on the surface of a food
To brown a food, usually meat, quickly on all sides using high heat. This helps seal in the juices and may be done in the oven, under a broiler, or on top of the range.
to cook in liquid that is barely at the boiling point
To cut food, often fresh herbs or dried fruit, with kitchen shears or scissors into very small, uniform pieces using short, quick strokes.
To cook a food in the vapor given off by boiling water
To cook food in liquid for a long time until tender, usually in a covered pot. The term also refers to a mixture prepared this way
the amount of minutes/ hours it takes to cook, rest, or prepare
To heat and brown (bread, for example) by placing in a toaster or an oven or close to a fire
to beat quickly and steadily by hand with a whisk or rotary beater
to soften solid fats, often by adding a second ingredient, such as sugar, working with wooden spoon or an electric mixer
to coat a food by sprinkling it with or dripping it in a dry ingredient such as flour or bread crumbs

two or more ingredients combined by passing a spatula down through the mixture, across the bottom, and up over the top. This process continues until the mixtures are combined. This traps air into bubbles in the product, allowing baked goods to rise.
to cut or break into thin pieces
to put through a sieve to reduce to finer particles
to remove a substance from the surface of a liquid
to cook food in a small amount of fat
to cook uncovered in the oven with dry heat
